From: wolf@merlin.att.com (Thomas Wolf)
Subject: Re: Tough! Quit griping! Was: Re: Don't use Motif for free sw: it now requires runtime royalties!
Date: Tue, 30 Nov 1993 17:48:19 GMT

Piercarlo Grandi (pcg@aber.ac.uk) wrote:
: HALLAM-BAKER> I think that the least users could do is to try to make
: HALLAM-BAKER> their comments constructive rather than destructive.

: ... and one such comment is: dear free sw developers, please don't use
: OSF Motif for any new programs you write:

: 1) There are complicated licensing issues that can cause problems to you
:    or to us, and that reduce the potential for usefulness and widespread
:    adoption of any free sw that depends on OSF/Motif.

If the free software is distributed in source form, I don't see how these
licensing issues could "cause problems" for the developer of the application
(unless the distributed source included Motif headers or something.)

: 2) There are free sw alternatives to OSF/Motif; among them Tcl/Tk, the
:    favourite, and then Interviews and, even if disliked by many, XView.
: It's just not worth the trouble writing free sw that uses OSF/Motif.
: That's simple _and_ constructive.

But it's probably also unrealistic.  I would venture to guess that most
of the free software out there is written by folks who either already program
professionally (developers) or hope to in the future (students).  These folks
are very likely to be using (or learning to use) Motif, simply because it's
become the "official" standard.  In their SPARE time,
these good souls are willing to give back to the community by developing
public domain software.
In essense, you're asking them to also spend their time to develop with one
of these "free" toolkits so you don't have to worry about licensing issues!

The software is free, for crying out loud.  If you don't like the developer-
imposed requirements for building/using the software - don't use it.

Just my $.02.
Tom

