From: hm@seneca.ix.de (Harald Milz)
Subject: Re: Comments from the "TAMU Crap" author
Date: Tue, 30 Nov 1993 07:57:18 GMT
Reply-To: hm@seneca.ix.de

I feel that I have to add my $0.02 from the electronic engineering point of
view, clearly supporting the XFree developers.

David E. Wexelblat (dwex@aib.com) wrote:
: > In article <2d5cdn$8ll@renux.frmug.fr.net> rene@renux.frmug.fr.net (Rene COUGNENC) writes:
: > >Ce brave Michaela Merz ecrit:
: > >
: > >> I'm a system- and networkprogrammer. I'm not to deep in graphics - so my 
: > >> question would be: Where is the problem to start  X and use cursor up 
: > >> or cursor down until there is a usable picture? 
: > >
: > >> Like tuning in a tv channel ... ?
: > >
: > >This is the good point of view.
: > >
: > >If an electronic set (Monitor, Video generator, washing-machine 10 BogoMips),
: > >made to be used by any end-user, can be destroyed just because you turned
: > >the wrong switch, then it is ill-designed.

: > Right.  So blame your hardware vendors.  Don't blame us when we do everything
: > in our power (which isn't much) to prevent this happening.

That's for sure. To go into detail: The output electric voltage of the 
horizontal transformer is directly proportional to the horizontal frequency
in _most_ designs. If you operate the monitor at a horizontal frequency that is
too high, the probability of high voltage breakthroughs on the output side of
the transformer or even in the secondary coil is very high. Those damages are 
irreparable. You have to replace the horizontal transformer after such an
event. Now guess you have purchased a not-too-expensive taiwanese monitor more
than half a year ago. You you think that any vendor will be able to supply the
correct transformer type? If you don't believe the power of the high voltage,
simply open your running TV set and touch the back side of the monitor
tube (NOOOO, don't do it!!). The voltage is higher than 15000 Volts which 
approximates the operating voltage of electrically powered railways.

This risk is much less when you buy an expensive, high-quality, microprocessor
driven monitor such as the modern EIZOs. Those will try to detect risky
frequencies and shut off the high voltage. But, however, even EIZO warns not
to operate the device outside of the specs, and _no_ vendor will warranty
repair a monitor with a burnt horizontal transformer. 

Hope this helps to clear the discussion. Do _not_ blindly check for horizontal
frequencies by walking through an Xconfig that you don't fully control. 
Immediately switch off your monitor when you see stripes or strange displays,
but at last, this has been written in the FAQ already.

Thanks again the XFree86 team for their work.

Ciao,
hm

